I am aiming to write an introductory guideline for empirical research. I will try to summarize some points that I wish I knew and explain some jargon that people generally assume you know. For example, empirical means based on observation rather than pure theory; and data is a collection of observations.

It includes some of my personal opinions and preferences, and I am far from expert. So take with a grain of salt :)

Basic points on R, RStudio, and Markdown

  • R is a software used for statistical analysis.

  • R Studio is an integrated development environment for R and Python. What that means to me is: a user interface that makes it easier to track what I am writing.

  • They are both free, open source, and widely used (both in the industry and academia)

    • This makes it easy to find help online and apply these skills elsewhere

  • I am writing this document in RMarkdown.

    • Markdown is a way to format text.
      • It makes some texts appear as headers, latex equations, lists, bold, italic etc based on what characters precedes or follows them
    • RMarkdown uses markdown to combine your code in R with texts, images, equations, etc.
      • It does this by grouping and interpreting certain lines differently than others. Those groups are called chunks.
      • a chunk is separated from the rest of the text by a chunk header and an ending line which i guess we can call an ender or footer)
      • chunk header example: ```{r clean_data, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} where the first argument in the curly brackets tells which programming language the code should be interpreted. the second argument is the name of the chunk and anything that follows the comma is an optional chunk setting.
      • When you Knit an rmarkdown file, the Render in the left bottom panel will run all the code in the file and produce the output (your report) in the desired format: html, pdf, or word
      • Go to RStudio -> Preferences -> R Markdown. By default, it should have Show output preview in Window. That means it will open a new window showing the output when you knit your rmd. I personally do not like that because it makes me have to keep switching between windows when I am making small changes. You can change it to Viewer Pane if you want your preview to appear on the right panel within the same window.

  • Essential file extensions to know:

    • file.R is an R script. this is pure R code
    • file.Rmd is an R Markdown. a combination of text and chunks of code
    • file.Rproj is an RStudio project.
      • RStudio project keeps track of what windows you had open and what objects were saved in your workspace last time

  • RStudio makes it very easy to use git alongside RStudio Projects. It is not required for this class, but I would recommend you to open a github account and keep your assignments and progress stored in a repository.

    • It takes time to get used to version control systems and terms, but that fixed cost pays off if you want a career in data, software, or empirical research in general.
    • For those who want to, here is a good place to start and another.

Getting Started

  1. Let’s download RStudio

  2. Now let’s create an R Project.

  • Go to File -> New Project. And select where you want it to be located in your computer.

    • Again, I want to remind that we do not have to create an R Project but it is useful to do so.

    • Normally a project is complicated on its own (with many subfolders, datasets, code scripts, and reports) and you would have a distinct R Project for every project you are working on. But if they are related (like assignments for a given class) and not very complicated, you may want to have a single main folder called ai_public and one ai_public.Rproj file in that main folder.

    • Whenever, you want to resume work from where you left off, you will open this ai_public.Rproj (or whatever name you have given it).

    • To keep things organized, you may want add subdirectories (subfolders) as you go throuhout the semester: assignment1, assignment2, raw_data, temp, figures, analysis/code etc.

  • By this point, we should have a main folder and an .Rproj file in it. When you open your .Rproj, your working directory will automatically be set to this folder (ai_public). If you are not using .Rproj, you will have to manually set a working directory (or it will use a default directory like “user/documents” all the time and save your files there).

  1. Now let’s create our first R markdown

  • Go to File -> New File -> R Markdown

    • R will make an example R markdown file that briefly explains what Rmd is and how you can use it.
    • From here onwards, you will organize this markdown file the way you want.
    • Divide your rmd by including headers (text preceded by pound(s))
    • Name your code chunks by what it does and take a look at chunk options (most important ones are echo, message, and fig).

  • Rstudio tips and built in cheatsheets:

    • Help -> Markdown Quick Reference.

      • a helpful page will open in the bottom right panel that tells you how to format your text in markdown

    • Help -> Keyboard Shortcuts Help. My favorite shortcuts are:

      • command+return for run the line
      • option+- for assign
      • shift+command+m for pipe

    • RStudio -> Preferences -> Appearance

      • You can select a theme and customize how your RStudio looks
      • You can do more customization in Pane Layout. I would recommend keeping the default panel layout until you understand what you can do with each panel first.

    • You can run codes line by line by command+enter or chunk by chunk by the run current chunk button next to the chunk header. Or you can select multiple lines and click the run button on top right of your script panel

    • When you don’t know a function or want to check its documentation (to see its optional inputs and examples) just type ?function_name()

Working on R

In any programming language, you would write functions for repeated tasks instead of copy pasting tens of lines again and again. Because R is very popular, people have written many useful functions for it (aside from the ones it already has). These additional functions are bundled in “packages” that you can install and load into your R.

# you install a package by install.packages("package_name")
# after installing a package, you need to load it from your library if you want to use it in that R script. This might seem repetitive but it is useful because having lots of packages loaded at once can lead to problems (such as similar function names)

# let's have a look at the packages we will use for this exercise

library(knitr) # this package is for knitting your rmd file

library(tidyverse) # this is a collection of very essential packages
# such as: dplyr (makes it easy to clean and process data), readr (read data stored in many different extensions), ggplot2 (very on demand data visualization tool), stringr (functions to edit, find, cut strings), ...
# Check out https://www.tidyverse.org/packages/ for more information on them

library(psych) # not widely used but I like its describe() function
# describe() that makes a summary statistics table for a given dataset. I find useful to have a quick look at the data

Now let’s do some basic mathematics with base r functions. Let’s say we have $12000 invested in a portfolio that yields 1.1% return a month on average and we add $700 to it every month. What would our expected equity be for the end of each month?

# you can use <- or = to assign a value to your variable or vector
# i've heard there is a small technical difference but idk what it is

r <- 0.011
equity <- 12000
recurr <- 700

for (i in c(1:12)) {
  equity <- (equity + recurr)*(1+r)
  print(paste0("expected equity at the end of month ", i,
               " is ", round(equity)))
}

# 4. Visualize

hist(iris$Petal.Width) # a similar story here as well. At this point, we should ask ourselves whether these are related.

plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$Petal.Width) # right away we see a clear positive relationship. And this makes sense that a longer petal would also be wider.

# let's see what else we can do with the function plot
plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$Petal.Width, pch = 5, col = 5) # pch tells R to use different symbols to point out the observations (eg pch = 1 is circle and pch = 2 is triangle). col is same but for color instead of shape.

# we can use these tools to symbolize the category an observation belongs to. In the iris dataset, species is a categorical variable
plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$Petal.Width, 
     pch = as.numeric(iris$Species), 
     col = rainbow(3)[iris$Species])

Iris with Tidyverse

We see that R on its own is already a pretty powerful tool. But we can do even more using packages that people before us prepared.

# we can take a look at the summary statistics altogether using describe() from psych package
describe(iris[-5], fast = TRUE) # iris[-5] means ignore the fifth column. i want to ignore it in the summary stats for now bcuz it's a string
##              vars   n mean   sd min max range   se
## Sepal.Length    1 150 5.84 0.83 4.3 7.9   3.6 0.07
## Sepal.Width     2 150 3.06 0.44 2.0 4.4   2.4 0.04
## Petal.Length    3 150 3.76 1.77 1.0 6.9   5.9 0.14
## Petal.Width     4 150 1.20 0.76 0.1 2.5   2.4 0.06
# we can use the dplyr package to produce a similar table by species
# dplyr is a super commonly used package to clean, transform, and summarize data
# an important thing to know in order to use it efficiently is the pipe operator   %>% 
# pipe takes the output of one line and makes it the first input of the function in the next line
# it makes things more intuitive and easy to follow (otherwise you will have to deal with lots crowded lines or nested parentheses to perform operations in the order you want)
# it's also efficient in terms of code length and legibility because most functions that transform data take the dataset as its first argument

iris_summary <- iris %>% # piping iris into group_by
  group_by( Species) %>% # piping grouped iris into select
  select(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width) %>% # selecting variables of interest
  summarise( sl_mean = mean(Sepal.Length), # 
             sl_sd   = sd(Sepal.Length),
             sw_mean = mean(Sepal.Width),
             sw_sd   = sd(Sepal.Width)
             )
head(iris_summary)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   Species    sl_mean sl_sd sw_mean sw_sd
##   <fct>        <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 setosa        5.01 0.352    3.43 0.379
## 2 versicolor    5.94 0.516    2.77 0.314
## 3 virginica     6.59 0.636    2.97 0.322
# the units are all in centimeters but let's still go ahead and normalize/standardize our variables as a practice. plus, it was mentioned in class as a good way to address the differences in magnitudes of units which will effect coefficient magnitudes and in turn how much or little they are shrinked

iris_standard <- iris %>% # pipe iris into rename
  rename(
        sl = Sepal.Length, # shorten names bcuz i will be referring to them many times 
        sw = Sepal.Width,
        pl = Petal.Length,
        pw = Petal.Width) %>% # pipe the iris with shortened names into mutate
  mutate( # mutate is a super useful function that helps you create new variables
       norm_sl = ( sl-mean(sl) ) / sd(sl),
       norm_sw = ( sw-mean(sw) ) / sd(sw),
       norm_pl = ( pl-mean(pl) ) / sd(pl),
       norm_pw = ( pw-mean(pw) ) / sd(pw) 
       )

# i often align the equals signs across lines to emphasize a pattern
# i use spaces to make it more visible which parentheses correspond to one another

head(iris_standard)

# in ggplot, we use + to add more characteristics to a plot. 
# you can save the plot as  an object and keep adding more stuff to it with +

scatter_petal <- iris %>%
  ggplot( aes( x=Petal.Length,y=Petal.Width, 
              color=Species, size=Sepal.Length)) + 
  # now we can color by a category and size by a numerical variable
  # aes stands for aesthetics. first we enter variables we want on the x-axis and y-axis
  geom_point(alpha=0.7) + 
  # geom_point makes it a scatter plot (good to compare continuous variables)
  # alpha (0,1) is a parameter for opacity: closer to 0 => more transparent.
  xlab("Petal Lenght") + ylab("Petal Width")+
  # label each axis with its variable
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Species"))

Probability Models

Now let’s build some probability models and compare their out of sample fit.

# Let's focus on base R for model building for now and we can learn and use ML libraries later in the course 
# I want binary variables for each category. It will be easier for me to build and test a simple model with base R functions using binary instead of categorical

iris_standard  <- iris_standard %>% 
  mutate(
    is_setosa = 1*(Species == "setosa"    ), 
    # using logical == to check if Species takes that value. 
    # mutate will loop the vector checking each row.
    # i multiply by 1 bcuz want the variable to be 1 or 0 instead of TRUE FALSE
    is_versic = 1*(Species == "versicolor"),
    is_virgin = 1*(Species == "virginica" ),
    # i want to include some squared terms
    sl2 = sl^2,
    sw2 = sw^2,
    pl2 = pl^2,
    pw2 = pw^2
    # be careful about squaring a normalized variable! 
    # think about why that might be poroblem
  )
  
# whenever you do something that is supposed to be random, you should set a seed. The computer will use this seed to randomize. 
# This is for reproducibility purposes (so that others can go and get the same results)
set.seed(121) 

# pick your favorite number.  I like 11 so I will pick 121
# normally, you want to set it to regular number like 100 or 1 so that you don't draw attention. but believe me playing with silly things like this can make boring tasks more engaging and fun

# Now split the data into train and test

iris_standard$rando  <- runif(150) # this is the R base way of creating a new variable. it's fast and easy if you are making or changing a single variable. otherwise, go with dplyr and pipe into mutate.

# here we are drawing a random number for each observation and I will use them to split the data. 
# the draws are from uniform distribution between 0 and 1. so one would expect one fourth of them to be below 0.25

iris_train <- filter(iris_standard, rando > 0.25)
iris_test <- filter(iris_standard, rando < 0.25)

# let's compare the count of observations of each category
# this is to see if we have balanced and comparable training and testing datasets
# since we cut it three quarters in train and one quarter in test
# ideally, we want around 37 obs per category for train and 12 for test
summary(iris_train$Species)
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##         37         36         38
summary(iris_test$Species)
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##         13         14         12
# it seems close let's run the models

# a linear probability model
setosa_lpm <- lm(is_setosa ~ norm_sl + norm_sw + norm_pl + norm_pw, 
            data = iris_train)  

summary(setosa_lpm) 
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = is_setosa ~ norm_sl + norm_sw + norm_pl + norm_pw, 
##     data = iris_train)
## 
## Residuals:

## -0.32067 -0.09897  0.01546  0.10501  0.41796 
## 
## Coefficients:

## Multiple R-squared:  0.9075, Adjusted R-squared:  0.904 
## F-statistic: 259.8 on 4 and 106 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# the model suggests that sepal width and petal length are the most important factors (sepal length and petal width are probably highly collinear to these two and thus not adding much info)
# let's store the predictions into iris_test
iris_test$setosahat_lpm <-  predict(setosa_lpm, newdata = iris_test)

# Out of sample mean squared error
mean( (iris_test$is_setosa - iris_test$setosahat_lpm)^2 ) # 0.02019706
## [1] 0.02019706
# even tho our model is very simple and sample size is small, this is not a bad out of sample MSE.
# let's include squared terms to see if we can improve

names(iris_train)                   
##  [1] "sl"        "sw"        "pl"        "pw"        "Species"   "norm_sl"  
##  [7] "norm_sw"   "norm_pl"   "norm_pw"   "is_setosa" "is_versic" "is_virgin"
## [13] "sl2"       "sw2"       "pl2"       "pw2"       "rando"
setosa_lpm2 <- lm(is_setosa ~ sl + sw + pl + pw + sl2 + sw2 + pl2 + pw2, 
            data = iris_train)  
iris_test$setosahat_lpm2 <-  predict(setosa_lpm2, newdata = iris_test)
mean( (iris_test$is_setosa - iris_test$setosahat_lpm2)^2 ) # 0.005017416 much better
## [1] 0.005017416
